Article.Abstract: The protective association between the human leukocyte antigen HLA-B53 and severe malaria was investigated by sequencing of peptides eluted from this molecule followed by screening of candidate epitopes from pre-erythrocytic-stage antigens of Plasmodium falciparum in biochemical and cellular assays. Among malaria-immune Africans, HLA-B53-restricted cytotoxic T lymphocytes recognized a conserved nonamer peptide from liver-stage-specific antigen-1 (LSA-1), but no HLA-B53-restricted epitopes were identified in other antigens. These findings indicate a possible molecular basis for this HLA-disease association and support the candidacy of liver-stage-specific antigen-1 as a malaria vaccine component.
Article.ArticleTitle: Molecular analysis of the association of HLA-B53 and resistance to severe malaria.

FirstInVivoProcess.InVivoProcessType: Environmental exposure to endemic/ubiquitous agent without evidence for disease

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Donors were from the Gambian village, Brefet, which has hyperendemic malaria. PBMC were collected at the time of year with lowest malaria transmission. PBMC were stimulated with a pool of peptides, each containing the HLA-B*3501-binding motif, and including the epitope and cp27, cp28, and cp29. IL-2 was added at 72 h. CTL assays were performed on day 8. Epitope-specific CTL lines were maintained by weekly restimulation with irradiated autologous epitope-pulsed BCL.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: CTL derived from 1 of 8 donors from a malaria-hyperendemic area of Gambia were stimulated by the epitope. CTL did not recognize two other naturally occurring variants of the epitope, cp28 (KPKDQLNY) and cp29 (KSKDELDY), and showed limited recognition of another variant, cp27 (KPKDQLDY).

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Donors were from the Gambian village, Brefet, which has hyperendemic malaria. PBMC were collected at the time of year with lowest malaria transmission. PBMC were stimulated with a pool of HLA-B*5301-binding peptides, including the epitope, and IL-2 was added at 72 h. CTL assays were performed on day 8. Epitope-specific CTL lines were maintained by weekly restimulation with irradiated autologous epitope-pulsed BCL.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: CTL derived from 3 of 6 donors from a malaria-hyperendemic area of Gambia were stimulated by the epitope. CTL lysis was inhibitable by anti-CD8 antibodies. The response was genetically restricted as demonstarted by the inability of CTL to lyse HLA-B*5301-mismatched target cells pulsed with the epitope. DNA sequencing of 9 Gambian isolates of the malaria parasite showed that the epitope sequence is conserved.

The epitope did not bind to HLA-B*5101 (HLA-B51) as assessed using the T2-B53(HLA-B*5301) cell line, which also expresses HLA-B51, in an MHC assembly assay. The epitope was added to lysates of 35S-methionine-labelled T2-B53 cells, and stable assembled class I molecules were precipitated with monoclonal anti-HLA antibodies and separated by one dimensional isoelectric focusing. The truncated peptide, ls9 (KPIVQYDN), also did not bind.

The epitope was shown to bind HLA-B*5301 (HLA-B53) as assessed using the T2-B53(HLA-B*5301) cell line in an MHC assembly assay. The epitope was added to lysates of 35S-methionine-labelled T2-B53 cells, and stable assembled class I molecules were precipitated with monoclonal anti-HLA antibodies and separated by one dimensional isoelectric focusing. The truncated peptide, ls9 (KPIVQYDN), did not bind.

FirstInVivoProcess.InVivoProcessType: Environmental exposure to endemic/ubiquitous agent without evidence for disease

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Donors were from the Gambian village, Brefet, which has hyperendemic malaria. PBMC were collected at the time of year with lowest malaria transmission. PBMC were stimulated with a pool of peptides, including the epitope, and each containing the HLA-B*3501-binding motif. IL-2 was added at 72 h. CTL assays were performed on day 8.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: CTL derived from 8 donors from a malaria-hyperendemic area of Gambia were not stimulated by the epitope.
